The paper deals with the generation of pseudorandom elements, which is a fundamental problem in randomized algorithms and data structures. This suggests that the paper could belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) category. The paper also discusses the time, space, and randomness complexity of randomized algorithms, which could place it in the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) category. The use of finite fields and constant time addition and multiplication suggests that the paper could also belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) category. The paper's focus on generating independent random values could place it in the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) category. Finally, the paper's use of polynomial factors in its space and time complexity suggests that it could also belong to the cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) category.
